    <h2>
        Close-Reading
    </h2>
    <p>

        In Persepolis, the graphic novel by Marjane Satrapi, we can observe the transformation of the main character as
        she embraces elements of Western culture. In the first panel, Marjane is depicted joyfully dancing and mimicking
        playing an electric guitar with her tennis racket. This playful act takes place in her room adorned with a new
        Iron Maiden poster, a gift from her parents during their trip to Turkey. It becomes evident that Marjane is
        becoming intrigued by English customs and developing a liking for heavy metal bands.

        Continuing to the next panel, Marjane assumes a modeling pose reminiscent of Kim Wilde, a renowned English
        singer. This gesture illustrates her growing fascination with the Western music scene and the influence it holds
        over her. In subsequent panels, we witness Marjane carefully selecting her attire, donning her Nike shoes and
        denim jacket while keeping her veil loosely draped on her head, revealing her hair. This deliberate choice
        showcases her evolving fashion sense and how she is beginning to adopt Western fashion trends.

        Although Marjane still wears her veil, it is notable that she no longer covers her entire head, signaling a
        gradual transition from her Iranian heritage to a more Western culture. She seeks to blend in with Western
        society, evident in her fashion choices and her alignment with the music and fashion culture prevalent in
        Austria, where she now resides.

        Through these visual depictions, Satrapi effectively portrays Marjane's journey of cultural assimilation and her
        desire to integrate into the Western world while retaining aspects of her identity.
